{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01Debqy13YFuPy9JFH3NNUeF","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The key error is:\n```\ndial tcp: lookup crdb-cluster-1.crdb-cluster.cockroachdb.svc.cluster.local: no such host\n```\n\nPod-1 (n2) is trying to connect to pod-0 at `crdb-cluster-0.crdb-cluster.cockroachdb.svc.cluster.local:26257`, but when it tries to make the connection, it's trying to look up `crdb-cluster-1.crdb-cluster.cockroachdb.svc.cluster.local` instead!\n\nWait, this is very strange. \n\nThe gossip client is attempting to connect to pod-0, but somehow the DNS lookup is resolving to crdb-cluster-1 instead. It's like the gossip mechanism is trying to route through node 1 to reach node 0, and that circular lookup is failing because node 1 doesn't exist in the cluster.\n\nActually, this might be a classic Kubernetes headless service issue—when a pod tries to resolve its own hostname to get its IP address for the connection handshake, the DNS might not have registered that pod as an endpoint yet, causing the lookup to fail.\n\nThe headless service selects pods based on their labels, but here's the catch: a pod's DNS name only becomes resolvable once it's marked as Ready, which requires passing the readiness probe. But the readiness probe needs the pod to successfully connect to the cluster first. So there's a circular dependency—the pod can't get a DNS entry until it's Ready, but it can't become Ready without being able to resolve its own name to connect.\n\nThe fix is to enable `publishNotReadyAddresses: true` on the headless service, which makes Kubernetes publish pod IPs in DNS even before they pass readiness checks. I'll patch the service with this setting.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":7490,"cache_read_input_tokens":40151,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":7490},"output_tokens":48,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"72bce601-3a3f-4730-b16b-22d47db88613","uuid":"5d898ad1-90db-44e9-8c32-4307c27c3173","request_id":"req_011CccB3NWNnBGJ955sak31i"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01Debqy13YFuPy9JFH3NNUeF","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"The root cause is clear: pod-1's DNS name (`crdb-cluster-1.crdb-cluster.cockroachdb.svc.cluster.local`) doesn't resolve because headless service DNS only includes Ready endpoints — a chicken-and-egg with the readiness probe. The fix is `publishNotReadyAddresses: true` on the headless service."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":7490,"cache_read_input_tokens":40151,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":7490},"output_tokens":48,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"72bce601-3a3f-4730-b16b-22d47db88613","uuid":"4b5af273-a929-4cde-b2bf-db44944d036b","request_id":"req_011CccB3NWNnBGJ955sak31i"}
