{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01KiR8VTogv53fg2viPUWMPJ","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"The CockroachDB cluster is fully up. Here's a summary of what was deployed and the two non-obvious issues that were resolved:\n\n**Resources deployed:**\n- `Service/crdb-cluster` — headless, ports 26257/8080, `publishNotReadyAddresses: true`\n- `Service/crdb-cluster-public` — ClusterIP, ports 26257/8080\n- `StatefulSet/crdb-cluster` — 3/3 ready, `podManagementPolicy: Parallel`, image `cockroachdb/cockroach:v24.1.0`\n- `PodDisruptionBudget/crdb-cluster-pdb` — `minAvailable: 2` (preserves quorum)\n- 3 PVCs, each 10Gi Bound\n\n**Cluster state:** All 3 nodes `is_available=true`, `is_live=true`.\n\n**Two issues resolved during bring-up:**\n\n1. **`podManagementPolicy: Parallel`** — The default `OrderedReady` policy never starts pod-1 until pod-0 is Ready, but pod-0 can't pass the `/health?ready=1` readiness probe until `cockroach init` is run, which requires all 3 pods to be running. Parallel launch breaks that deadlock.\n\n2. **`publishNotReadyAddresses: true`** on the headless service — Kubernetes only populates headless-service DNS for pods that pass the readiness probe. Without this flag, the pods' own FQDN (`crdb-cluster-1.crdb-cluster...`) couldn't be resolved during gossip setup, so nodes 2 and 3 could never complete joining the cluster. This flag ensures DNS entries exist for all pods regardless of readiness."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1086,"cache_read_input_tokens":49121,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1086},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"72bce601-3a3f-4730-b16b-22d47db88613","uuid":"7002c2d5-cae8-4b64-89ce-8ba85e614f6a","request_id":"req_011CccB6wHBxYQmUAAmpf16U"}
